[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+       42[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mThe problem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m The Encryption row mandates SSE-KMS on S3, a customer-managed KMS key on DynamoDB, and KMS encryption on CloudWatch Logs. Every decryption of an S3 prompt template, every DynamoDB GetItem or PutItem, and every CloudWatch Logs write requires a KMS API call to generate or decrypt a data key. With Lambda in a private subnet and no internet egress (the correct production posture), those KMS calls have no route. Without a KMS interface endpoint ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mcom.amazonaws.{region}.kms[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m), the Lambda will fail with [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mAccessDeniedException[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m or a timeout on the first S3 GetObject for the prompt templates, before the pipeline can even call Bedrock.[K
